 linking it to a longer history of childhood development. Drawing from a staggering array of primary sources, Bonnie Evans traces autism back to its origins in the early twentieth century and explains why the idea of autism has always been controversial and why it experienced a 'metamorphosis' in the 1960s and 1970s. Evans takes the reader on a journey of discovery from the ill-managed wards of 'mental deficiency' hospitals, to high-powered debates in the houses of parliament, and beyond. The book will appeal to a wide market of scholars and others interested in autism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutismzGreat BritainxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aBritain.  aMaudsley child psychotic clinic.  aSocial Psychiatry Research Unit.  aautism.  achildhood development.  aepidemiological research.  aglobal health crisis.  agovernment entities.  ametamorphosis.  apsychological theory.  asocial impairment.  asocial services.1 aEvans, Bonnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526110015zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526110015zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526110015/original  a978-3-11-128281-7 Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA